{"links": {"self": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/robocup3ds/pullrequests/14/comments/8827469.json"}, "code": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/osrf/robocup3ds/diff/osrf/robocup3ds:60abdc6bb3c9..54ec91f38569?path=include%2Frobocup3ds%2FGeometry.hh"}, "html": {"href": "#!/osrf/robocup3ds/pull-requests/14/_/diff#comment-8827469"}}, "deleted": false, "pullrequest": {"type": "pullrequest", "id": 14, "links": {"self": {"href": "data/repositories/osrf/robocup3ds/pullrequests/14.json"}, "html": {"href": "#!/osrf/robocup3ds/pull-requests/14"}}, "title": "Geometry_jliang_new"}, "content": {"raw": "Wouldn't it be better to call this `Spherical` instead of `Polar`? Wikipedia tells me [polar](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system) is 2D while [spherical](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system) is 3d.\n\nAlso it would be good to describe in the documentation what the vector elements mean (radius, polar angle, azimuthal angle)", "markup": "markdown", "html": "<p>Wouldn't it be better to call this <code>Spherical</code> instead of <code>Polar</code>? Wikipedia tells me <a data-is-external-link=\"true\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polar_coordinate_system\" rel=\"nofollow\">polar</a> is 2D while <a data-is-external-link=\"true\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spherical_coordinate_system\" rel=\"nofollow\">spherical</a> is 3d.</p>\n<p>Also it would be good to describe in the documentation what the vector elements mean (radius, polar angle, azimuthal angle)</p>", "type": "rendered"}, "created_on": "2015-08-05T17:04:57.304183+00:00", "user": {"display_name": "Louise Poubel", "uuid": "{5cfa2075-477b-4ded-bdb9-8d2479544ec4}", "links": {"self": {"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/users/%7B5cfa2075-477b-4ded-bdb9-8d2479544ec4%7D"}, "html": {"href": "https://bitbucket.org/%7B5cfa2075-477b-4ded-bdb9-8d2479544ec4%7D/"}, "avatar": {"href": "https://avatar-management--avatars.us-west-2.prod.public.atl-paas.net/557058:6ff